{
    "level": "A1–A2",
    "intro": "In this topic, you will practise <strong>am / is / are</strong>, the forms <strong>was / were</strong>, the pattern <strong>will be</strong>, negatives, questions, and <strong>there is / there are</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "Present Forms",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Start with <strong>am / is / are</strong> in simple sentences.",
            "example": "I am late. / She is ready. / They are here."
        },
        {
            "label": "Past and Future",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "Then add <strong>was / were</strong> and the pattern <strong>will be</strong>.",
            "example": "I was tired yesterday. / They will be here soon."
        },
        {
            "label": "Questions and There",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "After that, practise questions without <strong>do / does / did</strong> and the patterns with <strong>there</strong>.",
            "example": "Were they ready? / Will she be late? / There is a book on the table."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Starter set",
    "intro": "This subsection moves from the simplest forms to the past, the future, and the there-patterns.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "A1",
            "title": "Present Forms",
            "subtitle": "am / is / are in short affirmative sentences."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1",
            "title": "Negatives",
            "subtitle": "am not, is not, are not, and common short forms."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1",
            "title": "Questions and Short Answers",
            "subtitle": "Am I...?, Is he...?, Are they...? and short answers."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1–A2",
            "title": "Past Forms",
            "subtitle": "was / were, negatives, and questions in the past."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1–A2",
            "title": "Future",
            "subtitle": "will be, won't be, and simple future questions."
        },
        {
            "label": "A1–A2",
            "title": "There Is / There Are",
            "subtitle": "How to describe what is or is not in a place."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. What you will practise",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "am / is / are",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "You will see which form goes with <strong>I</strong>, <strong>he / she / it</strong>, and <strong>you / we / they</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I am tired. / She is a student. / They are at work.",
                    "ua": "Core models for state, identity, and place."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "was / were / will be",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "You will add past and future forms of <strong>to be</strong> so you can talk about what was true before and what will be true later.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He was at home yesterday. / They will be ready soon.",
                    "ua": "Past and future forms of the verb to be."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Questions and there",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "You will build questions and short answers, and separately describe what exists in a place.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Was she tired? / Will they be here? / There are two chairs in the kitchen.",
                    "ua": "Questions, short answers, and the pattern for existence in a place."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}
